late lunch break: letâ€™s talk about miscarriages and itâ€™s effects on women...and men! 
the tragedy of miscarriage has traditionally been private (we donâ€™t talk about it), an event grieved largely by the mother, on her own. this doesnâ€™t mean that men donâ€™t feel the pain as well (oh, they do!) but it is mostly grieved by women. people advise you that the sadness would grow less pronounced over time, especially following a successful pregnancy. not necessarily. 
studies show that the birth of a healthy baby does not resolve the mental health aftermath of miscarriage or stillbirth so it doesnâ€™t just â€œgo awayâ€. some women may mourn for much longer than expected, even after the birth of a healthy child. that's also true for men! studies have found that men grieve over a miscarriage more than once thought and that the impact of miscarriage is often underestimated in both men and women. 
did you know that a woman who has a miscarriage is at risk for depression and anxiety symptoms in subsequent years (up to 15 years after). post miscarriage ptsd can also develop with symptoms like flashbacks, hyperarousal and intrusive thoughts - the woman may spend enormous amounts of emotional energy trying to explain why it happened. she often blames herself (even when it is inaccurate) to help make sense of it. she sometimes torments herself with guilt and blame - â€œif i hadn't gone to work that dayâ€ or â€˜if i didn't argue with my spouse that morningâ€. this is a way of coping with the loss and itâ€™s part of the grief process however we need to acknowledge the feelings and not just dismiss it. 
tips on coping with miscarriage(s): â€¢ first step is to admit your sadness. itâ€™s okay to be sad. everything youâ€™re feeling is normal. â€¢donâ€™t rush your â€œgetting over itâ€. take your time. allow yourself off days to be sad just try not to stay there. â€¢donâ€™t let it put a strain on your relationship with your partner. you both need the emotional support for each other. remember he just lost his baby too. â€¢therapy helps - group or individual. and when it starts to affect your everyday life, seek professional help! â¤ï¸. #drsim #miscarriage #ptsd #grief #loss #depression #anxiety #psychmd #nycpsych #metoo

text:
#metoo 
in september,  i paid @cbtrn for a body paint photoshoot and i was sexually harassed during the process. some of the inappropriate physical contacts included: unnecessary message without consent, basically touching me everywhere especially lower body, spanking my butt, kissing my feet saying he has feet fetish on me, kissing me on my lip. he also used â€œarch more and show your clitorisâ€ kind of language during photo shoot. 
i have talked with about 20 people who did photoshoot with him and about half have encountered similar experiences like massage without consent, being licked, being drove around for half an hour which usually only a 5-minute-drive to talk about his sex stories, private part being painted for excessive long time (you know there isnâ€™t that much skin there).
i finally confronted with the photographer and he deflected the issue that he claimed to be suicidal and he needs to heal. doing art gave him the confidence to get back from surgery. i think this is just an invalid excuse. even though he promised to apologize in the public, he never did, so i think people should be informed about what is going on within this community. 
at the symposium arts & social justice breakfast: #metoo - what's next? hosted by @dance.nyc , i was shocked by how common the story was shared by dancers attended. so with support and love from friends and the community, i want to share some takeaways. 
1. artists, especially women in the theater/pole/aerial/circus/dance should support each other and be more open about sexual harassment. if this was brought up earlier, there wouldnâ€™t be. no slut shaming and believe in women.
	2. our bodies are our craft. we trained so hard to perform but it does not mean that people can take advantage of our bodies during art creation even with partnerwork, photoshoot, body paint.
	3. go with a friend.
	4. draw the boundary and have everything written in contract. you can find a template about anti discrimination and sexual harassment below and i am also happy to share the one i used for private terms. 	5. other resources: do check out dance/nyc's growing list of sexual harassment resources
	6. keep up with the hard work, and shareâ¤ï¸

(yâ€™all know!) and, after you have put on your mask, be generous with your help. pay it forward. you donâ€™t have to be an influencer or a professional or a scholar to offer it. whether itâ€™s sharing information and resources, telling your own story, or simply asking a fellow survivor â€œwhat do you need? how can i help?â€ saying â€œiâ€™m believe you.â€ do it. then listen. dialogue. keep asking questions. donâ€™t spout unsolicited advice or cliched affirmations. donâ€™t assume that you can relate. unfortunately and ashamedly i waited too long to start the process of voting from abroad and was not able to vote in this election. if all you have to do is get in your car and drive to your polling place, please do it. please vote, americans. and as you vote remember that the two greatest commandments are to love god and love people (all of the people).
. 
i have no excuse. i didn't think it would be as time consuming and mail-dependent to vote, but that's on me for not doing the research. be better than me, please!
. 
also, if you know who made this awesome picture, let me know because i can't find credit.
. 
#vote #rockthevote #fail #bebetter #intersectionality #blacklivesmatter #transrights #metoo #prochoice #immigrantsmakeamericagreat

text:
this text and photo was posted by @daralreayaen on twitter a year back. it was an account run by a former prisoner of dar al reaya, prisons for girls who run away from abuse or who dishonor their family in some way by disobeying. these places are located all over saudi. a woman i know was to one of these places recently. she confirms this is what women look like when going to the hospital or anywhere outside the institution- handcuffed and legcuffed and fully covered over the face. the photo is taken from isis but saudi dar al reaya prisons are similar and they are run by the government and the inmates are girls and women who simply disobeyed. i know it seems like a joke but i spoke to three witnesses who have been inside. phones are not allowed, no contact with the outside, except family members- the abusers the girl ran away from.
.
.
going to dar might be a womans only chance to escape abuse. but dont let the bastards grind you down- fight for your right, document your injuries from the guardian, get a lawyer before seeking help from a hospital and when they put you in dar demand to see that lawyer with name until they let you. many girls in there are stuck and wont get out unless the guardian takes them back or they are married off to another guardian, but those who fight hard and have a lawyer allready before going inside and the lawyer asks to see them... there might be a chance to make a case about the abuse you were put through by the guardian. but dont run away from the abuse, that will create a legal case against you! keep fighting in there to see the lawyer- never give up. 
#stopenslavingsaudiwomen #maleguardianshiphell #feminism #feminist #menafeminist #blm #blacklivesmatter #metoo #timesup #woman #girls #humanrights #womensrights #prison #daralreaya

text:
making a complaint at work can sometimes feel like setting off fireworks... so if you are being harassed and make a complaint my top tip to you would be:
be clear about the solution.
it helps to know what you want the outcome of making the complaint to be. how could it be resolved from your perspective? do you require said behaviour to stop, do you need an apology, does the person require disciplinary action and is the incident a criminal matter? there is a whole spectrum of answers to this question, but itâ€™s important to know what you want the solution to the report to be.

text:
today, i took both my kids in the double-stroller to vote.
.
.
i voted for freedom. freedom americans are promised and freedom we inherit. freedom for others to who come to our country seeking asylum and a better life.
.
i voted for equality. equality for all races, religions, and genders (even if i donâ€™t agree with certain lifestyles). everyone deserves the same rights no matter who they are.
.
i voted for health. for mental and physical health. for opportunities to be provided health care no matter what they can or canâ€™t afford. for the stigma of mental health and #metoo to disappear. for those with pre-existing conditions to not be punished.
.
i voted for more voice. voice of the people. voice of those under-represented: women, minorities, lgbtq+, immigrants, millennials. i vote for bipartisanship. .
.
i voted for education. for teachers to be laid their worth. we work more than 40 hours a week and although we donâ€™t actually teach summer months, we are still working our butts off. for every child regardless of socio-economic status or even citizen status to have a quality free education. for higher education to be cheaper and more available. for the stigma of technical and trade schools to disappear. for students to be able to learn how to learn and think for themselves and not memorize a test.
.
i vote for a greener earth. one filled with national and state parks that my children can explore. one with less pollution.
.
i vote for the right to bear arms (even though my household will never own one), but tougher restrictions and requirements on who can own what type of gun.
.
i vote for fairer taxes, lower property tax, more budget for public education, and more taxes for big businesses. for politicians being required to show their tax info if requested during campaigns.
.
i vote to support our troops, both active, retired, and discharged. i vote for support to the va.
.
i vote for mature politicians, not those who have temper tantrums on twitter.
.
i vote for the right to life. i vote for the right to worship (or not worship) how i may choose. i vote for tolerance. i vote for peace. i vote for love. i vote for what america should be.

text:
be it a saree or a dress, whatever you wear there is going to be someone out there judging your character .  we do not dress to impress or seek attention. we dress on par with comfort and choice. 
us , women, wearing a deep neck top or a short skirt triggers an adrenaline rush in men which gets out of control and leads to an act of disgust , a rape,  makes zero percent sense. imparting respect for women in men's eyes from a young age is what we need to practice. we need to educate our men like wise  putting forth the whole idea of #heforshe rather than suppressing our women.
there has been this phase on social media , a couple of months ago , i guess, when a lot of memes about the #metoo movement had been trending. i completely support the movement because it is absolutely necessary to empower the women who are not strong enough to speak freely regarding the gut wrenching incidences that have happened with them . if we cannot uplift the meek then i don't think we have rights to influence people with humour about them.
i believe shame lies in the eyes of the one who looks at you . so ladies, let's take a moment and remind ourselves that we are free to show as much skin as we like or cover our bodies as much as it pleases us. 
p.s. i drew that and i know i'm not great at it. ğŸ™ˆ

text:
â€œdrc is the rape capital of the worldâ€ the un secretary-general representive on sexual violence in conflict.

the sexual violence in eastern drc is the worst in the world. some stats show that girls as young as 10 years old are raped every day & often multiple times within their lifetime. some assaults are so bad they leave them with internal injuries so severe they are close to death.

while doctors such as noble peace prize winner denis mukwege, are doing amazing work to help women they are definitely inundated & overwhelmed.

we want to create opportunities for women recovering from such violence to rebuild their lives. sometimes left with disease, pregnancy and internal injury to face, their pain is often compounded by the abandonment of their husbands leaving them without any livelihood, community or financial support. we can help by investing in their potential so they can create a new future full of hope, on the journey of recovery.

i did it. i finally pushed the button. i've had this written for weeks, just sitting in my drafts waiting to be published, but it has taken me not just the past few weeks, rather almost 30 years to feel ready to share my stories. they've compounded on one another over time to the point that i can no longer harbor them inside. i'm ready to let go...to let them go, even though i know i'll still never feel free. but it is time. it's time for society, rules and expectations to change and that can't happen if we all remain quiet like they intended.

text:
today is the day! what are you voting for? our voice is our power. if you donâ€™t vote, you are in effect voting for our entrenched system. i vote to create a better world for my boys; to empower women; to #resist hate, oppression and racism; to end the patriarchy; to support equal rights; to protect our planet and our children. i vote for you. 
__
took these two kiddos with me to turn in my ballet this morning. i feel an incredible responsibility to teach them how to contribute towards a better world... to be inclusive, empathetic, use their voices in situations of injustice, use their privilege to uplift those without, support and believe women always and to vote! including them today was one of many small steps i hope will teach them these values and show them that even their voice and actions matter. 
__

text:
democracy requires showing up. ğŸ—³ğŸŒ»vote for what matters to you. to me, after living through the civil unrest and uprisings in ferguson, in my community, i couldnâ€™t ignore being black. there were tanks rolling down streets i used to drive through and children were being tear gassed. it became such a huge part of my identity that day and i started to fear for every black man in my family. i had to vote, my life and my families life literally depended on it. i collapsed on my parents bed and cried to my dad hysterically screaming â€œthey donâ€™t care about youâ€. iâ€™ll never forget that day that sparked this fire in me. i went back to school for the fall in california and switched my major to environmental science and policy, with a focus on environmental justice. i started spending more time outdoors and spent time as a park ranger volunteer. 
_______
i felt safe in nature, i was away from the chaos. 
________
i could breathe in deep breaths of fresh air and tune out the images of black bodies lying in the street or videos of black deaths flooding social media. the same desire i had to protect marginalized communities from harm started happening with nature. the safety it provided me and the space to practice self care was incredible, but it felt unfair. i started thinking about how other people of color just like me deserved equal access to safe natural spaces and access to clean air and fresh water resources for their overall wellbeing. they also deserved equal access to life. social justice and environmentalism are so interconnected for me. i canâ€™t separate the two. thatâ€™s why iâ€™m voting for a cleaner and safer future for the environment, minorities and other marginalized communities. ğŸŒ¿âœŠğŸ¾ vote like your life depends on it.

text:
75/100 ::a vote for our voices:: my feelings on voting today lie less on party lines and more in the quest to embody our voicesâ€”the means to our mutual liberation. our system is deeply flawed, it will likely take well past our lifetime to right this ship. we have so very much to reclaim. itâ€™s extremely hard to vote in such a broken system. today we can vote for the best of whatâ€™s in front of us, i know the options are often less then transformativeâ€”so vote with intentionâ€”using our voice to transform our world is a practice. vote to say you are awake and are witnessing our painful reality, that you are saying no to our current trajectory of violence. vote to let others know they are not alone in their persecution. vote to feel the weight of your own importance in your body. vote to validate your own meaningful existence. vote for your voice.
.
vote with heart open, with the energy of an out stretched hand: â€œi donâ€™t know your experience but i see and respect you.â€ many have let their pain so corrode their own hearts that they have fallen far beyond reason, where a language of hatred feels comforting and familiar in their own darkness. but we must act on behalf of all of us. we are all equal.
.
we are only free when we are all free.
.
you matter, your voice matters, we are strong togetherâ€”it starts here, in our waking up and forging pathways to one another. this is energy mountingâ€”itâ€™s an incredible and important moment in our history because in this destruction we are beginning something new, we are learning. the road ahead is long but there is joy hereâ€”in this moment, in speaking the word â€œvoteâ€ to one another, in this focused recognition of ourselves, we are mustering solidarity and protection. in our recognition of the deep oppression we are steeped in we choose action because we are tapped into our our sincere knowing that there is a better way. this is not a perfect process, nothing ever is, but there is joy here. #vote

text:
silence is a virtue, though not a choice
you look back at me silently, no core 
i plead you to speak, one word 
you simply stare, laid bare
white noise, keep me safe 
multiple choice, give me a sign 
i manipulate you, scroll, scroll, toll
people you may know, smile 
we can fight this tomorrow, alarm 
symptoms treated, muted
blue light, every night.

text:
words by @ascpoetry
â€¢
"with love, from lahore. as of today, i have received 94 submissions. almost half of them had to do with abuseâ€”physical, sexual, emotional. one particular story still follows me around. a woman, age 19, molested by her father's first cousin, age 30, while on vacation in pakistan. subsequently emotionally blackmailed & harassed by phone & threatened with suicide attempts if she ever told anyone or ceased contact. he once showed her a gun to his head over skype because she didn't send videos. it was abuse that followed her across continents. for years. that should make your bones tremble. pakistani culture often encourages victims to seek relief from pain only in god, islam, and the quran instead of therapy or legal justice. and for that reason, pakistan doesn't have very many christine blasey ford's or #metoo campaigns. instead, the author of this submission battled bulimia as a result of the abuse. she has privately and independently coped, as many woc end up doing, citing leaving her home to study abroad as an important component of her healing. this poem is for her & all the other ones just like her. an explanation as to why so many victims never come forward. we understand. we still believe you. #withlovefromlahore"

when my alma mater asked me to speak to the undergrads i considered a number of different topics that i could share with the students and faculty. 
and then i looked at the date they had booked me for: november 6. the day that our neighbours to the south, and a formidable presence on the world stage, are having their midterm elections. and i knew what i needed to say. 
so today we are talking about meeting god, not in the halls of power and prestige, but in the margins with those who have been overlooked, excluded, disposed of and silenced by systemic structures of inequality. and when we step into the margins together we experience a communion that is hard to describe, that reveals how god never stops working in the midst of our suffering and that jesus came to redeem every broken thing. 
get ready yâ€™all. itâ€™s gonna be a good one!

text:
since we are all getting personal about what we vote for, i have compiled a short list:
1. fair, equal and affordable healthcare access. 
2. the rights of our people, including trans, lgbtq, people of color, native people, #metoo, immigrants, sex workers, people practicing literally any other religion than catholicism/christianity. 
3. clean water. (why the is this still an issue?)
4. comprehensive gun laws cause ya know, kids shouldn't be killed while trying to get an education. 
5. better education for all, regardless of community economic status. and furthermore....
6. better wages for all, but especially: teachers, folks working min wage jobs.
7. continued division of church & state. 
8. reproductive protection because we know family planning drastically changes the course of a woman's life. 
9. voting representation in the house and senate for dc residents. washington, dc's 600k+ residents don't have any voting power on the matters that are affecting our country. 
and finally, 10. i'm voting for people who unify our country. there is no more room for folks screaming hate into our hearts, labeling "the other" as "the enemy of the people". #gtfo

@taylorswift @americaferrera @zoesaldana i'm cheering yall on for being voices of the people!

text:
on this first #electionday when i am an ex-pat, i am thinking about the #feminineuprising. i am thinking about a million women stepping up to say #metoo. i am thinking about how all this storytelling has awakened us, how everyone says there will be hell to pay on this election. i agree, it is time for all of us to stop sleepwalking, but i donâ€™t believe that the revolution will, to borrow a phrase, be televised. 
____
in honor of the silent revolution, i wrote a blog post all about this. when the cable stations finally shut down from all the election reporting, perhaps youâ€™ll take a read (check my bio for the link). _____
i used to think the revolution would happen through mass protests. we would clog the streets holding signs and shouting so that no business as usual could happen. they would have to listen. they would have to respond to our demands. but no -- we have overtired babies and mortgages to pay. and besides, there is no â€œtheyâ€ who is not â€œme.â€ _____
iâ€™ve stopped waiting for someone else to give me the code word. iâ€™ve stopped putting stock in poster paint. iâ€™ve started to do this on my own terms. 
_____
my revolution has led me to many choices, many places. this year, my revolution found me driving in a rusty van down a mexican highway, nursing my toddler to sleep on my lap and trusting very, very deeply. my revolution finds me waking up at dawn every day to meditate under the careful watch of venus, and then dancing in the blood-red rivers at kali maâ€™s feet as the sun cuts pink across the sky. my revolution finds me licking every single drop of juice from an orange, just picked from a tree and sliced open with a razor sharp stainless steel knife that i clean with the same reverence a warrior might give to her sword. 
_____
my revolution has me doing a million things every day, and you may never know about any of them. 
____
check out my words at sevamama.com/blog. and if you want to work with me to find your #intuitive revolution/evolution, send me a dm.

text: as a young woman living in america, i have never been so concerned for my future as i am right now. it seems every day that someone is trying to take away the rights that so many amazing, courageous women before me fought for. i will not let their strife go down in vain. i will do whatever i can to try to take control of this hell ride that has been the last 2 years. before you convince yourself that your vote doesn't matter, please think of the millions of women on medicaid who will soon have their health care stripped from them. please think of the fact that the mother fuckers in legislature are still trying to tell us what the fuck we can do with our bodies. please think of the sexual assault victims who still are being shamed away from pursuing prosecution against their attackers. please think of your sister, your mother, your daughter, and every woman that you love. your vote matters. so much.

text:
today is election day. i am voting to ensure future generations will have the strength, courage, and backbone to not shame, discredit or not believe survivors of sexual assault, abuse and misconduct. to ensure that our leaders from the top down do not treat women like pieces of meat, to be mocked, abused, sexualized, and laughed at. as a survivor of sexual assault, i wear this shirt in solidarity for all people who have been abused. this shirt arrived at my door with a cut slashed in the front, slightly imperfect, a little scarred, and bit different from the rest. after a feeling of slight annoyance to not receive a perfect new one, i realized the shirt came exactly how it should. the shirt, like me, may be a little worn, imperfect, slightly scarred, but it shouldnâ€™t be thrown out and tossed aside. my slight imperfections, my past, has fueled me to be stronger, more passionate, and emboldened to make change now. what happened to me as a teenager, will never release itself from my consciousness as i go through my everyday life. as much as you move on, you can never erase the past. i pray future generations will know how to protect themselves, how to respect each other so this gross abuse of women will become a thing of the past. until it does, we will fight. please vote today, for whatever you care about in your life. itâ€™s your right, your privilege, and your duty as a person lucky enough to live in this incredible country. #timesup #metoo #believewomen #believesurvivors #vote 
https://www.ibelievewomen.com
all proceeds from the sale of these shirts go to organizations working every day on the front lines, protecting and fighting for survivors.

text:
i donâ€™t regret the windy path, the healing, or the hard lessons that molded me into the woman that i am now. i am proud of this version of me. however, if i could go back and tell my 19-21 year old self one thing, it would be: stop numbing your trauma with alcohol. stop drinking because your only reason is "other people are" and definitely stop when it begins to make you feel sad.
.
when i was in syracuse last week, i bumped into someone who hasnâ€™t seen me since i graduated, since i was in that phase of life where i subconsciously numbed. in the conversation, she made a joke about how i used to be able to "drink other people under the table". not her fault for saying that because those were my actions and i grudgingly own them to be mine to be responsible for.
.
and then she looked at me and with a startled look in her eyes said: â€œyouâ€™ve lost weightâ€.
.
side note â€” this is not a compliment unless you know a human is actively in a weight-loss journey. alsoâ€¦ why do we still live in a society in which we verbalize thoughts about our fellow womenâ€™s bodies?
.
side note v.2 â€” iâ€™ve actually gained weight since starting my journey with weight lighting. i am the heaviest iâ€™ve ever weighed. though that truly doesnâ€™t matterâ€¦. what she was referring to was the beer weight and inflammation i used to hold in my face.
.
in the moment, i felt all the trauma i collected through my actions. i felt the struggles that used to be truly heavy burdens. and i realized and acknowledged that the assault was not the only trauma that occurred to my physical body at syracuse.
.
and that is okay, for our traumas and our healing make up who we are. these little moments that shine light on them are opportunities to heal further. they are invitations that we have indeed made progress. they are shimmers of truth and reminders that it is normal to struggle with being freaking human during times of hardship.
.
to my trauma body, i see you. i honor you. and i thank you for leading me to a path of continuous healing. and alcohol, iâ€™m thankful i no longer lean on you, that i can feel all my feelings in full force and still be whole.

text: every day we vote for women. we provide informed consent free of coercion and manipulation. we don't withhold information. we provide trauma-informed care. we offer and ask. we do things with women not to them. we understand that women exist in a system that wasn't built by them or for them, and as midwives and women, we exist in that system too. while i appreciate the conversations about "improving birth," the truth is that lydia and i aren't just talking about it, we're quite literally on the front lines of protecting women's rights every single day. it is not an easy job, and there are many days that in making it better for the women we serve, we make it harder for ourselves. let's not sit around discussing how we can make the world better, go vote for someone who will. #pleasevote #govote #fikamidwifery

text:
having been a teacher for many years, i had always wanted to organize a program that solely focused on empowering girls and preparing them for the world. i wanted to share inspirational stories about successful women and women who had changed the world. i wanted to provide a space for them to reflect, question, and have very real and open conversations about societal pressures and gender issues.  i wanted to give them the tools to help them successfully meet future challenges with strength and support. 
now as a mother to a 1-year-old girl, i realize more than ever the void that exists between women and the dire need to come together more to take action and change the world. today i hope to open up a space where all women young and old from whatever walks of life can feel inspired and share in the analyzing, understanding and defining what truly is our raw inner voice. #women #yeswecan #feminism #womanempowerment #inspiringwomen #motherhood #womensrights #metoo #metoomovement
